  "articleSummary": "The article argues that public benchmark scores (MMLU, HumanEval, etc.) are irrelevant for most AI‑driven products; what truly matters is how a model performs on a company’s own workloads. It advocates building “Evals”—task‑specific, deterministic tests and a golden‑case regression suite derived from real production failures—to catch silent errors, distinguish improvements from regressions, and avoid using users as informal testers. The piece walks through a practical three‑step workflow (define failure criteria, collect worst‑day examples into a golden set, and run both acceptance and regression tests) and contrasts cheap “LLM‑as‑judge” methods with costly human evaluation, positioning the former as unreliable. The tone is a pragmatic tutorial aimed at engineers and product teams responsible for deploying LLMs in real‑world applications, using the metaphor of “wearing a tuxedo of benchmarks” to frame the gap between headline scores and operational quality.",
